In this legend Virgil found the one theme that would serve his purpose. It dealt with the origins of Rome, while it also enabled him to sing the great- ness of his sovereign and patron, in whom he with so many of his contemporaries saw the regenerator, the second founder of the Roman state. It enabled him to link up the heroic legends of Greece with the early legends of Rome, and in his hands assumed a wider significance and a more definitely Roman character.
